He has held many important posts such as Philipline
Ambassador to the U.S. and more important President of the General

You old China Hands will laugh when
I tell you that for small chow we had among other things Quail eggs.
Personally I'd rather eat f'em a your or two later after they have
becone birds. Romulo, you will remember was with MacArthur on Corrigidor
and wrote a best seller which I think was called "I Saw the Pall of the
Philippines" or sonething like that. In his study he has autographed
pictures of four or five Presidents and most of the crowned beads of
the world and a whole case full of decorations.
He was the speaker
at the 250th aommencement of Washington University in Sto Louis and
was given a degree by Ethan Shepley. He is now President of the
University of the Philippines.
He and his wife are most charming
people. After we got to Honolulu one of the papers carried the piece
which I enclose. In his five points Romulo expresses ky own convictions
far better than I am able to do. I think you wild agree that it is
worth reading.
This morning wille Debby packed I took a ride on a Hydrofoil boat
from in front of the Manila Hotel to our old sea plane base at Cavite.
We made the round trip in an hour at a speed of about 40 miles per
hour.
With a full load of 70 passengers both ways.
One interesting
thing about Manila is that none of the newspapers, there are several,
publishes any daily weather information.
Why should they.
The weather
is always the same 80-90 except if there is a typhoon hovering amund.
That is well publicized.
To my mind a sad development has been the
acceptance of Tagabog as the official language.
This is simply a very
stupid expression of nationalism.
They are turning their baoks on the
wealth of English and Spanish literature to adopt a language only
recently reduced to writing with no back ground whatever.
